    Namaste friends,
     
    Bhakti yoga or the path of surrende=
r and devotion is indeed more suitable in this age. I did not mean to say o=
therwise.
     
    But just having an ishta devata is not enough to be "pr=
otected" from deep and troublesome instabilities when one's body-mind compl=
ex goes through a big transformation. Not every aspiring devotee becomes a =
Prahlada - some become Ravanas. After all, out of the two examples Leelaji =
gave below for "psychological disorder", the second lady "did much sadhana =
of Srirama". Even those who think of a deity and pray to him/her can end up=
 with hallucinations, mental and spiritual disorders, wrong (colored by one=
's conditioning and desires!) interpretation of internal/external experienc=
es and even madness.
     
    True surrender/devotion to ishta devata will=
 definitely protect one, but cultivating it is as difficult as cultivating =
detachment through wisdom! In fact, true surrender and detachment are almos=
t the same.
     
    This is why I said that *lightness of conditioning* i=
s the most important thing. One with dense conditioning will find SOME way =
to fail even if a great guru or god are ready to help.
     
    *        *=
        *
     
    Now, the question is: How do we reduce our conditioning=
? Unfortunately, there is no single magic bullet. Thinking of a god, mantra=
s, bhajans, japam, homam etc can help, but they need to be augmented by reg=
ular introspection and self-improvement.
     
    Taking mind away from it=
s current pre-occupations (e.g. "I am smart", "I am doing good sadhana", "I=
 am mad at X", "I did not get what I deserve in Y", "I am better than X", "=
I must have Y at any cost" etc etc) is key to eventually overcoming conditi=
oning, for these thoughts keep *reinforcing* the conditioning!
     
    To=
 reduce the regular pre-occupations of mind, different imagery/visualizatio=
n may work better for some people.
     
    One approach is to contemplate=
 god whenever possible, in the middle of any activity. You can imagine a be=
ing in your mind, either as an ideal/able person or as a principle/ideal/ab=
ility that exists in many beings, that is so perfect and fascinating for th=
e mind to contemplate that it does not care about other objects around that=
 are making shadripus and ashtapashas work on the mind. Whenever mind is ab=
out to entertain its regular debilitating pre-occupations, one can try to c=
ontemplate god instead.
     
    Mind is a wild animal. As Pi says in the =
movie "Life of Pi" about the tiger on the boat, wild animals can't be trans=
formed or domesticated, but they can be trained into some habits!
     
   =
 Whenever one is enjoying a sensual pleasure, if one thinks "the omnipresen=
t God is enjoying this thru this instrument" and starts contemplating the q=
ualities of that god instead of thinking too much about limited sense objec=
ts, one is better placed to reduce the damage done by shadripus. Whenever o=
ne is angry at someone for what they did, if one thinks "the omnipresent Go=
d is giving me the fruits of my karmas thru that instrument" and starts con=
templating the qualities of that god instead of being angry at someone, one=
 is better placed to reduce the damage done by shadripus. And so on.
     
=
    In the beginning, even contemplation of god becomes laced with ego. Eve=
ry now and then, the activity ends up becoming about oneself rather than ab=
out god ("*I* am doing this nice bhajan", "*I* am doing this nice homam", "=
I think *I* am making progress through this"). With effort and perseverance=
, one can avoid making it about oneself and keep it centered on the supreme=
 power that runs the show. Just as it takes a long time to train a wild ani=
mal, it takes a long time to train mind!
     
    Try to develop devotion =
and surrender. Based on all that you read and heard, develop of a concept/p=
rinciple of god that is so superb and fascinarting. Visualize/contemplate t=
hat concept as frequently as possible, especially when meditating. When min=
d veers off into other things, gently steer it back. Don't spend too much t=
ime dissecting what mind is doing and why. Just put it back gently into con=
templating god. Try to make it about god rather than about yourself.
     
=
    The main drawback of the sadhana of most people is that they make it ab=
out themselves at some level or the other. Though that is unavoidable, try =
to break free from it.
     
    *        *        *
     
    Finally, one=
 can try to overcome the limited sense of self and engage in selfless actio=
ns that benefit a larger set of people than oneself. What stops us from tru=
ly loving god is our deep and sub-conscious love for *ourselves* (i.e. our =
*limited* notion of self that drives the current body-mind complex). One wa=
y to overcome that is to selflessly love others. After all, other people ar=
ound us are as much replicas of god as we are. If we cannot empathize with =
them, love them and give them unconditionally, how can we ever hope to tran=
scend the limited sense of Self and truly love omnipresent God?
     

