        Namaste friends,
         
        Someone with p=
sychiatric problems may expereience what sounds like a Kundalini rise, but =
it may or may not be one.
         
        It must be conceded though that=
 Kundalini spontaneously rising through various nadis without one having go=
ne through proper preparation in this life (i.e. fine-tuning of one's attit=
ude and development of detachment) CAN create havoc!
         
        One =
may wonder how Kundalini may spontaneously rise in a layman with no sadhana=
, while many serious sadhakas may not experience it.
         
        Firs=
tly, Kundalini rise is NOT an achievement. It is just A SMALL STEP in overc=
oming one's current limited identity.
         
        Let me give an anal=
ogy. One wanting to move from one's small dilapidated house (this body-mind=
 complex) to a huge palace (realized Self) may first construct the palace o=
ver time and move into it when it is COMPLETE. Alternately, if one occasion=
ally goes and stays in the palace still under construction (analogy for out=
 of body experiences due to Kundalini rise), is it an achievement? In fact,=
 it comes with risks. The former approach is safer and one loses nothing in=
 it. Similarly, one can progress towards complete Self-realization without =
any out of body experiences. These are not my word's, but Maharshi Vasishth=
a's words to Lord Rama.
         
        Secondly, one does not get someth=
ing without wanting it and putting sufficient effort towards it. One may ha=
ve deeply desired a Kundalini rise in a previous life and may have put enou=
gh effort. As a result, one may be getting it now. But one may be unprepare=
d (and ironically may not even want it!) when it comes in this life.
      =
   
        As you do sadhana, try not to fancy too many specific desires. =
Nature has a delay mechanism in granting your desires (because of constrain=
ts on what Nature can give you right now, arising from YOUR OWN previous ac=
tions). So Nature sometimes gives you what you want LATE, when you no longe=
r want it or want something else. For example, one may pray for great wealt=
h one's whole life and be born as a rich but very sick man in next life. On=
e may not enjoy that wealth and pray whole life for health. In the life aft=
er that, one may be very healthy, but not have any knowledge or money. In a=
nother case, one may deeply desire to act in a famous film. One may be rebo=
rn as a tiger or a dog and act in a famous film, but not really enjoy that =
experience. Basically, people keep going in circles through various lives, =
always "seeking" something they are "missing".
         
        Anyway, co=
ming back to Kundalini, if one deeply desires an out of body experience giv=
en by a rising Kundalini and one's previous karmas constrain one from havin=
g it in THIS life, one may be born in next life with this specific desire d=
estined to fructify (if there is enough karmik force behind it).
         
=
        *        *        *
         
        Kundalini rise is not necessa=
rily scary or painful, if one is well-prepared in terms of attitude and det=
achment.
         
        Once I saw a chipmunk glued to a mouse trap. I w=
ent to free it and it panicked so badly and started to shake violently. I w=
ent to save it from a certain slow death and it was scared that I would kil=
l it!
         
        We are like that chipmunk, glued to the mouse trap =
called this body-mind complex and scared of being rescued from a certain sl=
ow death!
         
        If our ideas about who we are (viz this current=
 body-mind complex) are incorrect and if we are this "infinite Self" as sha=
stras say, won't a complete realization of that at some stage involve stepp=
ing out of this body-mind complex, without being scared?
         
        =
*        *        *
         
        Kundalini rise after most undesirable=
 conditioning is overcome, is far better than Kundalini rise forced when so=
me really undesirable conditioning is still left in one's system.
         =

        When one transcends one problematic notion about who one is and wh=
at one needs, another notion that lay buried deeper in consciousness may sp=
ring to the surface and torment one. If one overcomes the notion "I am the =
body", there may be another notion in one's body-mind complex that one's aw=
areness clings on to (e.g. a great doctor, a great leader, a great scholar,=
 a great saint etc). As an extreme example, if one person had a hidden deep=
 desire to be a great soul who rescues the world, he may fancy that he is a=
 re-incarnated X or Y who will rescue the world now. When one's self-awaren=
ess (i.e. Kundalini!) deeply clings to any such notion, it can cause havoc.=
 The person may show some signs of progress and yet remain in ignorance and=
 get stuck badly.
         
        An awakened Kundalini in a system with =
undesirable conditioning may accentuate one's weaknesses and wrong notions =
heavily and cause serious psychiatric and spiritual problems.
         
   =
     *        *        *
         
        The best approach I recommend is=
 to NOT think in terms of Kundalini and its rise. Just do sadhana, overcome=
 your weaknesses and improve your detachment over time. Again, I want to em=
phasize that detachment is not disgust or distaste for life/things/people a=
round you. Disgust is the other side of coin of attachment. It is a negativ=
e attachment.  
        Don't worry about whether your Kundalini rises or n=
ot. Worry about whether you are able to resist 6 internal enemies (shadripu=
s) and 8 bondages (ashta pashas) or not. If your ability to resist them is =
increasing, you are making progress. EVEN IF your Kundalini is fast asleep,=
 you are still making progress. When you completely overcome them, Kundalin=
i (your self-awareness) will automatically ascend to the top and meet Her L=
ord (true Self).
         *        *        *
         
        One word on=
 surrendering to a personal deity. Though true surrender is helpful, most p=
eople do not have it. They simply do business with god. Though people may b=
e offended by my words, this is the plain and bare fact.
         
        =
"I want X, I will pray to you and please give it to me", "I am scared of Ku=
ndalini rise, I will pray to you and please protect me" - all this is just =
a business deal. There is something you want and you ask god for it. True s=
urrender has no place for agendas, desires, demands or expectations. True s=
urrender is losing oneself in one's fascination for the qualities of Lord. =
True surrender is accepting anything Lord throws one's way (whether it is p=
leasurable or highly painful) as Lord's prasad and accepting it gratefully.=
 True surrender is thinking of Lord with fascination and pleasure, even in =
the face of (and during) Death.
         
        If one without true surre=
nder and with many desires and wrong notions experiences a Kundalini rise, =
one may still be trapped, despite thinking of a personal god. It is not tha=
t god does not want to "protect" one as said below. It is not about protect=
ing or endangering. If you go back to my "chipmunk glued to mouse trap" exa=
mple above, I was trying to protect it, but it was scared. Similarly, one's=
 conditioning makes one *run away* from God's protection! God's protection =
may seem to a conditioned mind like grave danger that one should run away f=
rom!
         
        *        *        *
         
        Whether throug=
h the path of wisdom or surrender, develop dispassion and detachment. Reali=
ze that all this is temporary and can be taken away anytime. Enjoy it while=
 you have and keep doing your best, but be prepared to lose everything anyt=
ime. Only detachment and a very light mental conditioning (very light desir=
es, dislikes etc) can protect one as one's Kundalini rises to meet True Sel=
f. Heavy conditioning and impurities in one's nadis will distract rising Ku=
ndalini (self-awareness) and stop Her from meeting True Self.
         
   =
     The real key is how light your conditioning is.
         
